ltaneously care for their children, often as single mothers. By offering a new way to understand how structural factors impact the daily experiences of poor women, Ain't No Trust highlights the pervasiveness of distrust in their lives, uncovering its hidden sources and documenting its most corrosive and paralyzing effects. Levine's critique and conclusions hold powerful implications for scholars and policymakers alike.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aLow-income single mothersxEmploymentxUnited States. 0aLow-income single mothersxEmploymentzUnited States. 0aLow-income single mothersxServices forxUnited States. 0aLow-income single mothersxServices forzUnited States. 0aLow-income single mothersxSocial conditionsxUnited States. 0aLow-income single motherszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520956919423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520956919.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles